Flammability is affected by weather conditions (
 Bond, 1997; 
 Keeley & Syphard, 2017). Fire danger indices—based on ambient temperature, relative humidity, wind speed, and rainfall—are commonly used to rate the fire-proneness of weather conditions (
 Dowdy et al., 2009; 
 Noble, Gill & Bary, 1980; 
 Sirca et al., 2018). Flammability is also influenced by fuel properties such as the amount of flammable plant material (fuel load), packing ratio and chemical composition (
 Brooks et al., 2004; 
 Burger & Bond, 2015; 
 Curran et al., 2017). For instance, greater fuel loads or volatile substances can increase fire intensity (
 Baeza et al., 2002; 
 Saura-Mas et al., 2010).
